An array is a collection of elements of the same data type stored in contiguous memory locations. It allows storing multiple values under a single variable name.

**Syntax:**
```c
data_type array_name[size];
```

**Example:**
```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    // Array declaration and initialization
    int marks[5] = {85, 90, 78, 92, 88};

    // Accessing array elements
    printf("First student marks: %d\n", marks[0]);
    printf("Third student marks: %d\n", marks[2]);

    // Modifying array element
    marks[1] = 95;

    // Display all elements using loop
    printf("All marks: ");
    for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        printf("%d ", marks[i]);
    }

    return 0;
}
```

**Output:**
```
First student marks: 85
Third student marks: 78
All marks: 85 95 78 92 88
```

**Key Points:**
- Array index starts from 0
- Elements are stored in consecutive memory locations
- Size must be specified during declaration
- Can be single-dimensional or multi-dimensional
- Useful for storing collections of similar data

