**Class:**
A class in C++ is a user-defined data type that serves as a blueprint for creating objects. It binds data and functions together that operate on the data.

**Syntax:**
```cpp
class ClassName {
    access_specifier:
        data_members;
        member_functions();
};
```

**Object:**
An object is an instance of a class. When a class is defined, no memory is allocated until objects are created from that class.

**Example:**
```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

// Class definition
class Student {
    public:
        string name;
        int roll_no;

        void display() {
            cout << "Name: " << name << endl;
            cout << "Roll: " << roll_no << endl;
        }
};

int main() {
    // Creating objects
    Student s1, s2;

    // Accessing class members
    s1.name = "Ram Sharma";
    s1.roll_no = 101;

    s2.name = "Sita Rai";
    s2.roll_no = 102;

    // Calling member functions
    s1.display();
    s2.display();

    return 0;
}
```

**Output:**
```
Name: Ram Sharma
Roll: 101
Name: Sita Rai
Roll: 102
```

**Key Points:**
- Class is a template/blueprint
- Object is a real entity created from class
- Multiple objects can be created from one class
- Each object has its own copy of data members

