Logical operators in C are used to combine multiple conditions and return a boolean result (true or false).

**Three Logical Operators:**

1. **Logical AND (&&):**
   - Returns true only if both conditions are true
   - Example: `(age >= 18 && has_license == 1)`
   - This returns true only if age is 18 or more AND has_license is 1

2. **Logical OR (||):**
   - Returns true if at least one condition is true
   - Example: `(marks >= 80 || attendance >= 90)`
   - This returns true if either marks are 80+ OR attendance is 90+

3. **Logical NOT (!):**
   - Reverses the logical state of the condition
   - Example: `!(age < 18)`
   - This returns true if age is NOT less than 18 (i.e., 18 or more)

**Truth Table:**
```
A     B     A&&B   A||B   !A
false false false  false  true
false true  false  true   true
true  false false  true   false
true  true  true   true   false
```

**Example Program:**
```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int age = 20;
    int has_license = 1;

    if (age >= 18 && has_license == 1) {
        printf("You can drive\n");
    }

    if (age < 18 || has_license == 0) {
        printf("You cannot drive\n");
    }

    if (!(age < 18)) {
        printf("You are an adult\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

