**Array:**
- Collection of elements of the same data type
- Elements are stored in contiguous memory locations
- Accessed using index number
- Example:
```c
int marks[5] = {85, 90, 78, 92, 88};
printf("First mark: %d", marks[0]);
```

**Structure:**
- Collection of elements of different data types
- Members can have different data types
- Accessed using member names (dot operator)
- Example:
```c
struct Student {
    int roll;
    char name[50];
    float marks;
};
struct Student s1 = {101, "Ram", 85.5};
printf("Name: %s", s1.name);
```

**Key Differences:**
1. **Data Types:** Array - same type; Structure - different types
2. **Access:** Array - index; Structure - member name
3. **Memory:** Array - contiguous; Structure - may not be contiguous
4. **Purpose:** Array - store similar data; Structure - store related data of different types

