A structure in C is a user-defined data type that allows grouping of variables of different data types under a single name. It is used to represent a record.

**Syntax:**
```c
struct structure_name {
    data_type member1;
    data_type member2;
    // ... more members
};
```

**Example 1: Basic Structure**
```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

// Define structure
struct Student {
    int roll_no;
    char name[50];
    float marks;
};

int main() {
    // Declare structure variable
    struct Student s1;

    // Assign values
    s1.roll_no = 101;
    strcpy(s1.name, "Ram Sharma");
    s1.marks = 85.5;

    // Access and display
    printf("Roll Number: %d\n", s1.roll_no);
    printf("Name: %s\n", s1.name);
    printf("Marks: %.1f\n", s1.marks);

    return 0;
}
```

**Example 2: Structure with Array**
```c
#include <stdio.h>

struct Book {
    char title[100];
    char author[50];
    float price;
    int pages;
};

int main() {
    struct Book b1 = {"C Programming", "Dennis Ritchie", 450.50, 300};

    printf("Book Title: %s\n", b1.title);
    printf("Author: %s\n", b1.author);
    printf("Price: Rs. %.2f\n", b1.price);
    printf("Pages: %d\n", b1.pages);

    return 0;
}
```

**Output:**
```
Roll Number: 101
Name: Ram Sharma
Marks: 85.5

Book Title: C Programming
Author: Dennis Ritchie
Price: Rs. 450.50
Pages: 300
```

**Key Features:**
- Groups related data of different types
- Members accessed using dot (.) operator
- Useful for database records, complex data organization
- Memory allocated for all members combined

